</md></sn><sn><md>### Shallow Copy Behavior

The `slice()` method creates a **shallow copy** of the selected elements:

* If elements are **primitive values**, they are copied by value.
* If elements are **objects**, only the references are copied (not the objects themselves).

```javascript
const arr = [{ a: 1 }, { b: 2 }];
const newArr = arr.slice();

newArr[0].a = 100;

console.log(arr[0].a); // Output: 100 (both arrays refer to the same object)
```
</md></sn><sn><md>### Comparison with Similar Methods

| Method     | Modifies Original Array | Returns New Array | Description                                          |
| ---------- | ----------------------- | ----------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| `slice()`  | ❌ No                    | ✅ Yes             | Extracts part of an array                            |
| `splice()` | ✅ Yes                   | ✅ Yes             | Adds/removes/replaces elements in the array          |
| `split()`  | ❌ No                    | ✅ Yes             | Splits strings into arrays (for strings, not arrays) |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Use Cases

* Creating a **copy** of an array.
* Extracting a **subarray**.
* Cloning an array before modifying it.
* Converting **array-like** objects (like `arguments`) into real arrays:

